                        %p.theme-text3
                          Pietas is a Latin word that can be translated as piety or devotion, and refers to someone's dutiful acceptance of the obligations placed on them by fate, by the will of the gods, and by the bonds of family and community. From the first lines of the poem,
                          %span.inline-character Virgil
                          describes
                          %span.inline-character Aeneas
                          as being remarkable for his piety, and "pious" is the most-used adjective to describe Aeneas throughout the poem. Aeneas always places these obligations above…
                        %em
                          %a{:href => "/lit/the-aeneid/themes/piety"} (read full theme analysis)
